In  Hinduism,  practically  every religious act or rite has to be ç
preceded by a sa<209>kalpa. It is actually a declaratory formula giving ç
not only the details of the day according to the pa<210>c<193><209>ga ç
(traditional calendar) but also the purpose behind the act.
A  typical  sa<209>kalpamantra  should contain the names and other ç
details of the kalpa, manvantara, yuga, geographical position of the ç
place of performance, year, solstice, month, fortnight, date and day ç
of the week, as also the name of the person who is performing and ç
the purpose.
Any rite not preceded by such a sa<209>kalpa will become fruitless.
See <MS>KALPA<D>, <MS>MANVANTARA<D> and <MS>YUGAS.
