When dharma (righteousness) abandons its followers because they have ç
ignored it or distorted it, and, adharma (villainy) quickly fills ç
its place, masquerading, perhaps, as a better substitute, God is obliged ç
to intervene! (vide Bhagavadg<200>t<193> 4.7,<|>8) He may do so either ç
by directly descending to this earth as an avat<193>ra (incarnation) ç
or by infilling certain chosen persons to accomplish his task of restoring ç
the balance in favour of the former.
During  the  period  preceding  the advent of <185>a<209>kara (also ç
known as <185>a<209>kar<193>c<193>rya), the San<193>tana-dharma (theAncient ç
and Eternal Religion, now commonly known as Hinduism) based on the ç
Vedas, was facing stiff opposition from several quarters.
Buddhism with its ·<220>nyav<193>da (nihilism), Jainism with its ·y<193>dv<193>da ç
or anek<193>ntav<193>da (which states that a thing can be described ç
