<185>a<209>kara was extraordinarily brilliant and mastered all the ç
·<193>stras (scriptural and other treatises) taught to him even at ç
a young age.
Unfortunately, father <185>ivaguru died soon, leaving <185>a<209>kara ç
entirely to the care of his mother °ry<193>mb<193>.
Being indrawn by temperament and having realised the transitory nature ç
of the world, through the direct experience of the death of his father, ç
<185>a<209>kara decided to embrace sa<221>ny<193>sa (monastic life). ç
The only impediment in the path was the mother's love andattachment, ç
and the need to take her permission!
By a quirk of destiny, this came about sooner than expected. One day ç
when he was taking bath in the river P<220>r<207><193>, a big crocodile ç
caught him. As he was struggling for life, and finding that he was ç
waging a losing battle, he appealed to his wailing mother who was ç
standing on the bank, to give him permission to take sa<221>ny<193>sa ç
mentally and die in peace.* She had no alternative but to oblige. ç
However, the crocodile left him as mysteriously as it had caught him. ç
As per the scriptural injunctions, he now had to take formal sa<221>ny<193>sa. ç
Most unwillingly the mother gave him the permission to do so, but ç
