<185>a<209>kara was a prolific writer. He has left behind him a voluminous ç
literature which can be categorised into three groups: Bh<193><218>yas; ç
Prakara<207>as; and, Stotras.
Bh<193><218>yas are his erudite expositions of the basic works on ç
Ved<193>nta philosophy and Hindu religion. Apart from the ten Upani<218>ads, ç
the Brahamas<220>tras and the Bhagavadg<200>t<193> (collectively ç
called the prasth<193>natraya), he has written bh<193><218>yas on ç
the Vi<218><207>usahasran<193>ma (vide Mah<193>-bh<193>rata, Anu·<193>sanparva, ç
ch. 149), the Sanatsuj<193>t<200>ya (Udyogaparva, ch. 40-45) and ç
the Lalit<193>tri·at<200> also.
As regards the prakara<207>as which are simple treatises on Advaita ç
Ved<193>nta, quite a large number of them have been attributed to ç
him. Of them, the following works  are  popular:  Aparok<218><193>nubh<220>ti, ç
°tmabodha, Laghuv<193>kyav<216>tti, Upade·a-s<193>hasr<200>, ç
V<193>kyav<216>tti and Vivekac<220>d<193>ma<207>i 
A very large number of stotras or hymns, on almost all the well-known ç
deities of the Hindus, are ascribed to him. It is rather difficult ç
to segregate a few and declare thatthey are definitely his. However, ç
the following stotras are definitely his compositions according to ç
scholars seasoned in <185>a<209>kara's style of writing as also other ç
available evidence: °nanda-lahar<200>, Bhajagovindastotra, Dak<218>i<207><193>-m<220>rtya<218><219>aka, ç
Da·a·lok<200>, Gop<193>l<193><218><219>aka, Harim<200><195>estotra, ç
Man<200><218><193>pa<210>caka, <185>iva-bhuja<209>gapray<193>ta, ç
Sop<193>napa<210>caka and Vi<218><207>u<218>a<219>pad<200>.
Apart from these, two works on tantra†the  Prapa<210>cas<193>ra  and  the ç
Saundaryalahar<200>†are also attributed to him.
@SB = His Philosophy
<185>a<209>kara being the greatest propagator ofAdvaita Ved<193>nta, ç
holds the view that the basic truth or reality behind this universe ç
of multiplicity, of myriad names and forms, is one and one only, advaita, ç
the one without a second. This reality called Brahman appears as the ç
many due to the peculiar, indefinable, factor called m<193>y<193>. ç
Just as semidarkness hides the real nature of a rope (lying on the ç
road) as rope and projects in it a snake (as it appears to us then) ç
which is not there, so also m<193>y<193> hides the true nature of ç
Brahman (as Sat-Cit-°nanda, existence-consciousness-bliss) and projects ç
on that base, this manifold universe. Even as a bright light reveals ç
the rope as rope, dispelling the snake-appearance, thereby removing ç
all fear, in the same way, j<210><193>na or right knowledge removes ç
the illusion brought about by m<193>y<193>.
@SPACE1 = 
Though <185>a<209>kara has not defined and explained m<193>y<193> ç
in detail, he has given enough indications in his writings that it ç
acts like anexisting positive force (bh<193>var<220>pa) but disappears ç
mysteriously once it is neutralised by j<210><193>na (knowledge or ç
direct experience).
Once this basic standpoint that this multiple universe is a projection ç
of m<193>y<193> on Brahman is accepted, <185>a<209>kara is prepared ç
to give it a greater degree of reality (called vy<193>vah<193>rikasatt<193> ç
or empirical reality), because, then only the reverse process of attenuating ç
and eliminating it is possible. Otherwise the whole structure of s<193>dhana ç
based on this empirical reality collapses!
It is at this secondary level (of empirical reality) that <185>a<209>kara ç
concedes the process of creation of the world as given in the Upani<218>ads, ç
the multiplicity and limited nature of the j<200>vas (bound souls), ç
®·vara (God, Brahman in the garb of the Creator) as responsible for ç
the creation, sustenance and dissolution of the world and the entire ç
process of s<193>dhana by the j<200>vas to regain their lost (essential) ç
nature.
As  a  corollary,  <185>a<209>kara  also acknowledges that m<193>y<193> ç
has its individual counterpart, generally called avidy<193> or aj<210><193>na ç
(ignorance, nescience). It is this avidy<193> that makes a j<200>va ç
(the individual) feel identified with the body-mind complex, see the ç
external world of duality, feel attraction or repulsion towards its ç
objects, work to get what he wants, thus getting into the bondage ç
of the cycle of births and deaths.
Once this j<200>va awakens and takes to the path of s<193>dhana and ç
realises his true nature as sat-cit-<193>nanda, the <193>tman (the ç
Self or the soul), his avidy<193> is totally dispelled.
The body may continue to function for some time due to pr<193>rabdha ç
karma. When it falls, he is fully liberated, being merged in Brahman, ç
never to be born again.
The individual who realises his <193>tman-nature and continues to ç
live in the embodied state till the pr<193>rabdha expires, is called ç
a j<200>vanmukta (`the liberated, even while living'). In this state ç
his subjective reactions to the world have totally changed though ç
he continues to see the world as before. The man, who has discovered ç
the rope as rope in good light, will continue to see it as a snake ç
in semidarkness, since the cause of the illusion is outside himself. ç
However, his personal reaction to it has totally changed from one ç
of fear to that of indifference or even amusement.
@SB = Epilogue
If <185>a<209>kara is fondly remembered even today†twelve centuries ç
after his advent† both by the intellectual classes and the simple ç
masses†it is not a little due to his all-round personality. His bh<193><218>yas ç
and prakara<207>as have enriched the knowledge of the former. His ç
stotras on various deities commonly worshipped by the latter, have ç
infilled them with devotion. The various miracles he is said to have ç
performed†like the raining of golden myrobalans in the house of the ç
poor lady or changing the course of the P<220>r<207><193> river to ç
facilitate bathing by his aged mother†restored faith in the power ç
of tapas (austerity) and divine grace in the minds of the sceptics. ç
By putting a stop to the bizarre practices that were being carried ç
out in the name of religion by certain sects and cults, and converting ç
their votaries to purer ways of life, he saved them and the society ç
too. His convincing victories over the non-Vedic and anti-Vedic religions ç
restored theVedic religion to its pristine glory. The reorganisation ç
of Hindu monasticism made it more people-oriented through his direction, ç
viz., prav<193>sa (touring) and prac<193>ra (preaching).
Finally, his tender affection towards his lonely mother and the filial ç
duty he discharged (fulfilling his promise) towards her during her ç
last moments, speaks volumes of the intensely human aspect of his ç
personality.
He did all these things and much more, never for a moment lowering ç
his own dignity of demeanor or slipping from the sublime heights of ç
monastic life.
Only an avat<193>rapuru<218>a (an incarnation of God) can accomplish ç
such feats.
