<185>a<209>karadeva is the brightest star of the Vai<218><207>ava ç
Movement in Assam and north-east India, whose contribution is no less ç
than that of <185>r<200>k<216><218><207>a Caitanya (<MS>A.<|>D.<D> ç
1485-1533) in Bengal and Orissa.
He was born at the village °lipukhuri (Nowgong district, Assam). His ç
parents were Kusumbara and Satyasandh<193>. He lost his parents very ç
early in life and was brought up by his grandparents. He got a good ç
education in a Sanskrit school and also developed his god-given talents ç
in music, painting and composing poems.
@SPACE1 = 
He was married and had a daughter. His wife died immediately afterwards.
He went out (when he was thirty-three) on a long pilgrimage and travel ç
spread over twelve years. He visited many places including K<193>·<200>, ç
V<216>nd<193>ban, Mathur<193>, Kuruk<218>etra, Dv<193>rak<193> and ç
R<193>me·varam. During these visits, the strong current of Vai<218><207>avism ç
he noticed everywhere due to the influence of saintly poets like Vidy<193>pati ç
(15th century <MS>A.<|>D.<D>), Jayadeva (12th century <MS>A.<|>D.<D>) ç
and <185>r<200>k<216><218><207>a Caitanya †whom he met for a short ç
period†practically converted him from his <185><193>kta moorings to ç
the Vai<218><207>ava creed.
After returning to his place he was forced by his close relatives ç
to marry a second time. This perturbed him much. However, the chance ç
arrival of Jagad<200>·a-mitra†a great pundit and a travelling mendicant†helped  him  to  regain  his ç
balance and peace. Jagad<200>·amitra stayed with him and taught him ç
the Bh<193>gavata. <185>a<209>karadeva's conversion to Vai<218><207>avism ç
was now complete. This inspired him to translate the Da·amaskandha ç
(the tenth book of the Bh<193>gavata containing K<216><218><207>a's ç
