@SB = Cult
Though <185>a<209>karadeva adopted Vai<218><207>a-vism as his religion ç
he evolved his own form of it and developed a cult. He carved a wooden ç
image of K<216><218><207>a, called it Madanagop<193>la and established ç
it in his prayer-hall with elaborate ceremonies. The prayer-hall itself ç
was called `n<193>maghar'.
He started his own form of initiation called `·ara<207>a'. This had ç
three categories or aspects: n<193>ma·ara<207>a, guru·ara<207>a andbhakti·ara<207>a ç
a la Buddhist ·ara<207>as (Buddha, Dharma and Sa<209>gha).
In other prayer-halls built under his supervision or guidance, he ç
installed the Bh<193>gavata-book instead of K<216><218><207>a's image ç
on a wooden pedestal. This new method averted the need for formal ç
worship, that too only by a br<193>hma<207>a, and associated rituals. ç
All devotees, irrespective of caste or religion, could offer a simple ç
service to the book before congregational prayers called k<200>rtan.
The simple process of initiation he adopted was to transmit the mantra ç
hare k<216><218><207>a, hare r<193>ma.
The Bh<193>gavata was adopted not only as the scripture but also ç
as the object of worship.
@SB = Philosophy
According to <185>a<209>karadeva, K<216><218><207>a is the Supreme ç
God who is a person (Puru<218>a, Puru<218>ottama, Parame·vara and ç
N<193>r<193>-ya<207>a), eternal, omniscient and omnipotent. The puru<218>as ç
(or j<200>vas, individual souls) are many and are His a<221>·as or ç
parts (vide Bhagavadg<200>t<193> 15.7). The insentient prak<216>ti ç
(nature) is also his.
<185>a<209>karadeva lays great stress on bhakti, that too d<193>syabhakti ç
(considering oneself as a d<193>sa or servant of God). The most important ç
aspect of this is eka·ara<207>atva (total surrender or dedication ç
to God).
Though mok<218>a or salvation (freedom from transmigratory existence) ç
is accepted, the devotee is indifferent to it since he enjoys devotion ç
to God much more.
@SB = Works
<185>a<209>karadeva did not write commentaries  on  the  prasth<193>natraya  (See ç
